<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<exercise xml:id="reading-question-set-operations-and-containment" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Set operations and containment
  </title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m> S </m> and <m> T </m> be sets.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that <m> S \cap T = S </m> if and only if <m> S \subseteq T </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since <m> S \cap T \subseteq S </m>, it suffices to show that <m> S \subseteq S \cap T </m> if and only if <m> S \subseteq T </m>. To that end, note that if <m> S \subseteq S \cap T </m>, then (1) of <xref ref="proposition-set-operations-and-containment"/> implies that <m> S \subseteq T </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Conversely, we note that <m> S \subseteq S </m>, so that if <m> S \subseteq T </m>, then (1) of <xref ref="proposition-set-operations-and-containment"/> implies that <m> S \subseteq S \cap T </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that <m> S \cup T = S </m> if and only if <m> T \subseteq S </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since <m> S \cup S \cup T </m>, it suffices to show that <m> S \cup T \subseteq S </m> if and only if <m> T \subseteq S </m>. To that end, note that if <m> S \cup T \subseteq S </m>, then (2) of <xref ref="proposition-set-operations-and-containment"/> implies that <m> T \subseteq S </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Conversely, we note that <m> S \subseteq S </m>, so that if <m> T \subseteq S </m>, then (2) of <xref ref="proposition-set-operations-and-containment"/> implies that <m> S \cup T \subseteq S </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that <m> S \setminus T = S </m> if and only if <m> S \cap T = \emptyset </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        First suppose that <m> S \cap T = \emptyset </m>. Then <m> x \notin T </m> for all <m> x \in S </m>, and so
        
        <md>
          S \setminus T = \setmid{ x }{ x \in S \textrm{ and } x \notin T } = \setmid{ x }{ x \in S } = S
        </md>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Conversely, now suppose that <m> S \cap T \neq \emptyset </m>. Then <m> x \in S \cap T </m>, and so <m> x \in S </m> and <m> x \in T </m>. Since <m> x \in T </m>, <m> x \notin S \setminus T </m>. So <m> x </m> is an element of <m> S </m> but not <m> S \setminus T </m>; we conclude that <m> S \setminus T \neq S </m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
